text: infundibulocystic basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that affects the outer layer of the skin. It is characterized by the presence of cysts and follicular differentiation, which means the cancer cells look like they are arranged in hair follicles. This type of skin cancer can be treated with surgery or other treatments such as Mohs surgery.
Nodular Basal Cell Carcinoma is a type of skin cancer. It is characterized by elevated, pearl-shaped nodules with telangiectasia on the surface and periphery.

Metatypical Basal Cell Carcinoma is a type of Basal Cell Carcinoma characterized by intermediate typology between Basal Cell Carcinoma and Squamous Cell Carcinoma. Another name for this condition is Metatypical Carcinoma, and it can also be referred to as Skin Metatypical Carcinoma or just Metatypical Basal Cell Carcinoma.

Pigmented basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that appears as pink or brown growths on the skin. These tumors are usually found in areas exposed to the sun, such as the face, neck, and hands. They may also occur in other parts of the body. Pigmented basal cell carcinoma can be treated with surgery, and it has a good prognosis when detected early and treated properly.

Anal margin basal cell carcinoma is a specific type of skin cancer that occurs in the perianal skin area, which is the skin surrounding the anus. It is also known as Basal cell carcinoma of Perianal skin.

Anal margin carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that occurs in the anal margin, which is where the canal meets the outside skin at the anus. It is characterized by abnormal proliferation of epithelial cells and is typically located in the perianal skin. The term "anal margin carcinoma" is often used interchangeably with "perianal skin carcinoma" and "carcinoma of anal margin."

Skin nasal cell carcinoma with sebaceous differentiation is a type of basal cell carcinoma. Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is the most common form of cancer, and it typically occurs on sun-exposed skin areas like the face, neck, and ears. BCCs can also occur in other parts of the body that have been exposed to the sun. They often appear as a pearly or translucent nodule, a flat scar-like lesion, or a verrucous growth with a waxy, scaly surface. If left untreated, BCCs can grow larger and invade surrounding tissue, leading to disfigurement and even bone erosion if it spreads to the skull. Surgical excision is typically recommended for treating BCCs, either through curettage or electrocautery.

Basal cell carcinoma of the external ear is a type of skin cancer that originates in the basal cells of the skin. It typically appears as a small, pearly or waxy bump on the skin's surface and may be sensitive to sunlight. If left untreated, it can grow larger and deeper into the skin, potentially causing disfigurement or even metastasis to other parts of the body. Treatment options for basal cell carcinoma include surgical excision, cream or lotion applications of 5-fluorouracil (a chemotherapy agent), and other medications such as imiquimod or photodynamic therapy.

External ear carcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the external ear. It is also known as carcinoma of the external ear. This type of cancer has abnormal proliferating cells that are derived from epithelial cells, which are responsible for the growth and maintenance of tissues in the body. The exact cause of this cancer is not yet fully understood, but it can be caused by exposure to certain chemicals or radiation. It is important to seek medical attention if you notice any symptoms of external ear carcinoma, such as a lump or swelling in your ear. Early detection and treatment are crucial for successful recovery.

Micronodular basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that is characterized by the presence of solid tumor nodules. It is also known as skin micronodular basal cell carcinoma, and it is one of several types of basal cell carcinomas. Basal cell carcinomas are the most common type of skin cancer, and they can occur on any part of the body that is exposed to sunlight. They are generally not life-threatening, but they can cause significant disfigurement if left untreated. Treatment options for basal cell carcinoma may include surgery, radiation therapy, or creams that are applied directly to the skin.

Gynatresia is a term used to describe an obstruction or blockage of the female reproductive tract, specifically involving the vagina. This can result from a variety of factors such as infections, inflammation, or physical obstructions like tumors or congenital abnormalities. In some cases, gynatresia can lead to infertility if the blockage prevents sperm from reaching the egg. It is important for individuals with gynatresia to seek medical attention and treatment in order to address the underlying cause and prevent complications.

Adamantinoid basal cell epithelioma is a type of skin cancer, which is a malignant growth of cells originating from the epidermis. This specific type of skin cancer is characterized by its slow-growing nature and its ability to infiltrate surrounding tissues. It is also known as basal cell carcinoma - adamantinoid, melanotic adamantinoma of the skin, or skin adamantinoid basal cell epithelioma. Treatment options for this type of cancer may include surgery, radiation therapy, and/or topical medications. It is important to consult with a dermatologist for proper diagnosis and treatment.
Fibroepithelial basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer. It has synonyms such as Fibroepithelioma of Pinkus and Pinkus tumor.

Morpheaform Basal Cell Carcinoma is a specific type of Basal Cell Carcinoma. It is also known as Cicatricial Basal-Cell Carcinoma and Morphea-Type (Sclerosing) Basal Cell Carcinoma. These terms refer to the same condition, but use slightly different terminology to describe it.

Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is a type of skin cancer that originates in the basal cells of the skin. It is considered to be one of the most common forms of skin cancer, with over 3.5 million cases diagnosed annually in the United States. BCCs typically occur on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the face, neck, and ears.
There are several subtypes of BCC, including:
1. Squamous cell carcinoma (SCC): This type of BCC develops from squamous cells in the skin's outer layer. It is more aggressive than other types of BCC and can spread to nearby tissues or organs if left untreated.
2. Basal cell carcinoma (BCC): As mentioned, this type of BCC originates in the basal cells of the skin. It is the most common subtype of BCC and is typically characterized by a slow-growing, pearly or waxy growth on the skin's surface.
3. Clear cell carcinoma (CCC): This type of BCC develops from cells in the middle layer of the skin called the dermal papillae. It is less common than other subtypes and can occur anywhere on the body. CCC may be more aggressive than other types of BCC and tends to spread more quickly.
4. Nodular BCC: This type of BCC develops from cells in the middle layer of the skin called the dermal papillae. It is less common than other subtypes and can occur anywhere on the body. Nodular BCC may be more aggressive than other types of BCC and tends to spread more quickly.
5. Micronodular BCC: This type of BCC develops from cells in the middle layer of the skin called the dermal papillae. It is less common than other subtypes and can occur anywhere on the body. Micronodular BCC may be more aggressive than other types of BCC and tends to spread more quickly.
It's important to note that while basal cell carcinoma is generally considered a low-risk cancer, it can still cause significant damage if left untreated. Therefore, it's essential to seek medical attention if you notice any suspicious growths or lesions on your skin. Early detection and treatment can help prevent the cancer from spreading and causing more serious complications.

Adenoid basal cell carcinoma is a type of basal cell carcinoma, which is characterized by the presence of thin strands of basaloid cells forming a reticulate pattern. Adenoid basal cell carcinoma is also referred to as skin adenoid basal cell carcinoma.

That is correct. Follicular basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that is characterized by the presence of follicles in its appearance. It can occur on any part of the body, but is more commonly found on the face and neck. The exact synonyms for this condition are "follicular (pilar) basal cell carcinoma" and "Skin Follicular Basal Cell Carcinoma". It's important to note that while this type of cancer can be treated, it is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect you have skin cancer.

Scimitar syndrome is a congenital heart disease that affects the venous drainage of the right lung. It occurs when there is partial or complete anomalous curved venous drainage from the right lung to the inferior vena cava, which can lead to various issues like pulmonary artery hypoplasia and dextroposition of the heart. The exact synonyms for scimitar syndrome include Halasz syndrome, congenital venolobar syndrome, hypogenetic lung syndrome, mirror-image lung syndrome, pulmonary venolbar syndrome, total anomalous pulmonary venous return and vena cava bronchovascular syndrome.

infiltrative basal cell carcinoma is a type of basal cell carcinoma that is characterized by the formation of thin, small clusters in an infiltrative growth pattern.
exact synonym skin infiltrating basal cell carcinoma

Superficial basal cell carcinoma, also known as multifocal or superficial multicentric basal cell carcinoma, is a type of basal cell carcinoma. It is characterized by the presence of multiple distinct tumors that are located on the surface of the skin and have a relatively shallow depth.
Superficial basal cell carcinoma typically appears as one or more raised, shiny bumps or lesions on the skin's surface. These lesions may be pink, red, brown, or even white in color, and they often have a slightly waxy or translucent appearance. The tumors can occur anywhere on the body but are most commonly found on sun-exposed areas such as the face, neck, and ears.
It is important to note that while superficial basal cell carcinoma is generally considered to be less aggressive than other types of skin cancer, it can still spread if left untreated. Treatment options for this condition include surgical excision, cryotherapy, and topical chemotherapy.

Vulva basal cell carcinoma is a type of vulva carcinoma, which is a specific type of skin cancer that affects the vulva, or external female genitalia. Basal cell carcinoma is a common form of skin cancer and can occur on various parts of the body, including the face, neck, arms, legs, back, and even the genitals. It typically appears as a pink or brown, shiny bump or nodule on the skin that may be itchy or bleed when scraped. In some cases, it can also appear as a scar-like lesion or a pink, scaly patch of skin. If left untreated, basal cell carcinoma can grow and invade surrounding tissues, causing damage to the affected area and potentially leading to disfigurement or even cancerous spread to other parts of the body. Early detection and treatment are crucial for ensuring the best possible outcome.

Cystic basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that appears as an outgrowth or growth on the surface of the skin. It is characterized by its cystic appearance, which means it has air pockets inside it. This type of cancer can be aggressive and may require surgical intervention to remove it completely. It's also important to note that this condition should not be confused with a simple cyst or a skin cyst, as they are different conditions altogether.

Basal cell carcinoma is a common skin cancer that usually appears as a slow-growing, shiny, pink or red bump on the face, neck, or other exposed areas of the body. It's also sometimes called "basal cell carcinoma, nodular type" to distinguish it from another type of basal cell carcinoma, called "basal cell carcinoma, infiltrative type."
Sarcomatoid basal cell carcinoma is a rare and aggressive subtype of basal cell carcinoma that tends to grow quickly and spread to other parts of the body. It's also sometimes referred to as "skin sarcomatoid carcinoma" or "basal cell carcinoma, sarcomatous type."
It's important to note that while these different subtypes of basal cell carcinoma can look quite similar at first glance, they are actually distinct types of skin cancer with different treatment and prognosis. If you have any concerns about a growth on your skin, it's always best to consult a dermatologist for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Signet ring basal cell carcinoma is a subtype of basal cell carcinoma, which is a common skin cancer. Signet ring basal cell carcinoma gets its name from the presence of a distinctive signet ring appearance under the microscope, and it often has a lower risk of recurrence than other subtypes of basal cell carcinoma.

bone giant cell tumor is a type of benign giant cell tumor, it results in the presence of multinucleated giant cells. It has exact synonyms like Giant cell neoplasm of bone, Giant cell tumor of bone, Giant cell tumour of bone and bone giant cell tumour. Additionally, it is related to giant cell myeloma and osteoclastoma.

Radiculopathy is a type of peripheral nervous system disease that occurs when the nerve roots in the spine are compressed or irritated, causing symptoms such as pain, weakness, numbness, and tingling. It can be caused by conditions such as herniated discs, spinal stenosis, or spondylolisthesis, and can also result from injury or compression of the nerves.

Yes, that is correct. Polyradiculopathy refers to a condition where multiple nerves are affected by compression or damage, leading to symptoms such as pain, numbness, and weakness in the affected area. It can be caused by various factors such as herniated discs, spinal stenosis, or tumors, among others. Proper diagnosis and treatment are crucial for managing the symptoms of polyradiculopathy and preventing further complications.

Polyradiculoneuropathy is a type of peripheral nervous system disease that affects the nerves in the spinal column and the peripheral nerves. It is characterized by symptoms such as pain, numbness, and weakness in various parts of the body. The exact cause of polyradiculoneuropathy can vary depending on factors such as age, health history, and lifestyle. Treatment options may include medications, physical therapy, or other interventions to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Epidermolysis bullosa acquisita is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the skin and connective tissue. It is characterized by recurrent blisters that form in response to minor trauma, such as friction or scratching. These blisters are often found on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet. The condition is caused by abnormal immunoglobulin levels, and it has a location in the skin's surface and connective tissue. Epidermolysis bullosa acquisita is also known as acquired epidermolysis bullosa.

That is correct! Non-gestational choriocarcinoma, also known as choriocarcinoma, is a type of cancer that develops in the placenta. It occurs when the cells of the placenta grow uncontrollably and form tumors. It can also spread to other parts of the body, such as the lungs, brain, and bones. Treatment for non-gestational choriocarcinoma may include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

Ebola hemorrhagic fever is a viral infectious disease that causes severe symptoms such as bleeding, fever, and muscle weakness. It is transmitted through contact with bodily fluids of an infected individual or animal, contaminated surfaces, or medical equipment. The symptoms include fever, headache, joint pain, muscle aches, sore throat, weakness, diarrhea, vomiting, stomach pain, rash, red eyes, hiccups, and internal and external bleeding. It has a hemorrhagic component, which means that it can cause severe bleeding. Ebola virus disease is an exact synonym for this condition.

Marburg Hemorrhagic Fever is a viral infectious disease characterized by hemorrhagic fever, which has its material basis in the Orthomarburgvirus marburgense. It can be transmitted through contact with the body fluids of an infected person and causes symptoms such as fever, chills, headache, myalgia, maculopapular rash on the trunk, nausea, vomiting, chest pain, sore throat, abdominal pain, diarrhea, and bleeding. It is also known as Marburg Disease or Marburg Virus Disease.

Erdheim-Chester disease is a rare type of non-Langerhans cell histiocytosis. It is characterized by the proliferation of lipid-laden macrophages in tissues and the presence of multinucleated giant cells. This condition can lead to sclerosis of long bones and failure of affected organs.
Non-Langerhans cell histiocytosis (also known as non-LCH) is a type of histiocytic disorder characterized by the accumulation of histiocytes that do not meet the criteria for Langerhans cells.

Burning mouth syndrome (BMS) is a condition characterized by persistent, burning sensations in the mouth, without any identifiable cause. It can affect any part of the mouth and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as dryness, tingling or numbness, and changes in taste. BMS is estimated to affect 1-2% of the population and is more common in women than men. The exact cause of BMS is unknown, but it has been linked to a variety of factors including diet, stress, hormonal imbalances, autoimmune disorders, and certain medications. Treatment for BMS typically involves managing symptoms with over-the-counter pain relievers or prescription medications, as well as addressing any underlying causes through changes in diet and lifestyle.

Parovarian cyst is a type of female reproductive system disease that involves the development of epithelium-lined fluid-filled cysts in the adnexa adjacent to the fallopian tube and ovary. These cysts are usually benign, but can become large and cause discomfort or other symptoms if they rupture or twist. Treatment typically involves monitoring the cyst with ultrasound and surgical removal if it becomes problematic.

tinea favosa is a type of tinea capitis, which is a fungal infection that results_in the scalp, glabrous skin or nails. It has a material basis in Ascomycota fungi and can cause scarring. The disease starts with yellowish cup-shaped crusts called scutula formed at the surface of a hair follicle with the shaft in the center of the raised lesion, which oozes and leaves a red base once the crusts are removed. It is also known as favus.

Tinea capitis is a type of dermatophytosis, which is a contagious fungal infection that results from the union of something that is on or near the scalp and eyelashes, eyebrows or hair of the head. It can cause symptoms such as itching of the scalp, pus-filled lesions, and patches of hair loss, sometimes with a black dot pattern. Tinea capitis is caused by Ascomycota fungi that belong to a group called dermatophytes. The exact synonyms for tinea capitis include Scalp ringworm, Trichophyton rubrum tinea capitis, and dermatophytosis of scalp or beard. It is related to Dermatophytosis of scalp.

Variegate porphyria is a type of acute porphyria that occurs due to a deficiency in the enzyme protoporphyrinogen oxidase. This enzyme is responsible for the production of protoporphyrin, which is essential for the formation of red blood cells. As a result, individuals with variegate porphyria have difficulty producing enough red blood cells and may experience symptoms such as abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fatigue. It is also possible for variegate porphyria to be inherited through an autosomal recessive pattern of inheritance.

lymphocele and lymph cyst are terms used to describe a condition in which the lymphatic system is affected. both terms refer to the presence of excess lymph fluid in the tissues, leading to swelling and discomfort. it is important to note that this condition can be caused by various factors such as injury or infection, but also certain medical conditions like cancer, herpes, HIV/AIDS, and other viral diseases. Lymphocele can occur in any part of the body, but are most common in the legs, groin, neck, and armpit. It is important to consult a medical professional if you suspect that you have lymphocele, as it may require treatment such as surgery or radiation therapy.

Ciliary body cancer is a type of iris cancer, which is a malignant neoplasm of the ciliary body. It can also be referred to as a malignant tumor of the Ciliary body or simply as ciliary body disease. The exact synonyms for this condition include neoplasm of the ciliary body, tumor of the Ciliary body, and cancer of the iris.

Ciliary body disease is a term used to describe an iris-related condition that occurs within the ciliary body, which is a part of the eye located between the iris and the cornea. It can be a part of iris diseases in general or a specific disease affecting this area. The term "ciliary body" specifically refers to the ciliary processes and muscles that help regulate the shape and size of the pupil, so diseases involving this area may have an impact on vision.

posterior mediastinum cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the posterior mediastinum, which is the area behind the heart and between the lungs. It can be caused by various factors such as smoking, exposure to radiation, and certain viruses or bacteria. Symptoms may include chest pain, shortness of breath, coughing up blood, and fever. Treatment options depend on the stage and location of the cancer but may include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

Epithelioid cell melanoma is a type of melanoma that is characterized by the presence of epithelioid cells, which are a subtype of macrophage. These cells are found in the tumor and can affect the behavior and prognosis of the disease. Epithelioid cell melanoma is also known as epithelioid melanoma. It is important to differentiate this type of melanoma from other subtypes, such as classic or acral melanoma, as each subtype has different treatment options and prognoses.

cervical cancer is a disease that occurs in the cervix, which is the lower part of the uterus. It is also known as cervical neoplasm or cancer of the cervix. The exact synonyms for cervical cancer include cervix cancer, cervix uteri cancer, and neoplasm of the uterine cervix. Additionally, it can be referred to as a tumor of the Cervix Uteri or uterine cervical neoplasm.

That is correct. Malignant breast melanoma, also known as malignant melanoma of the breast, is a type of breast cancer that arises from melanocytes, which are cells responsible for producing melanin in the skin. It is important to note that while the term "breast melanoma" may be used colloquially, it is technically incorrect and should not be used in medical contexts. Instead, the correct terminology is "malignant breast melanoma" or simply "malignant melanoma of the breast."

Apparent mineralocorticoid excess syndrome is a type of steroid inherited metabolic disorder, which means it's passed down through genes and affects how the body processes certain hormones. This condition is characterized by low levels of aldosterone, a hormone that helps regulate blood pressure, and other symptoms such as high blood pressure, low potassium levels, and metabolic alkalosis. It is caused by mutations in the HSD11B2 gene on chromosome 16.

Myasthenia gravis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the nervous system. It has symptoms such as muscle weakness, double vision, ptosis, dysarthria, dyspnea and shortness of breath. The condition is caused by antibodies that attack acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction.

Schnitzler syndrome is a type of hypersensitivity reaction that presents with chronic urticarial rash and monoclonal IgM gammopathy. It also has symptoms such as intermittent fever, arthralgia (joint pain), and lymphadenopathy (swollen lymph nodes).

Intracranial embolism is a type of cerebrovascular disease that occurs when blood clots or other debris travel through the bloodstream and become stuck in the small blood vessels within the brain. This can lead to reduced blood flow and oxygenation to the affected brain tissue, resulting in potential neurological damage or even death if not treated promptly.
Intracranial embolism is often caused by conditions such as atrial fibrillation, deep vein thrombosis (DVT), or cancer that spreads to the brain. It can also be caused by traumatic injury to the head or spine. Symptoms of intracranial embolism may include sudden onset of severe headache, confusion, weakness or numbness in the face or extremities, and difficulty speaking or understanding speech. If you suspect that you or someone you know is experiencing an intracranial embolism, it's important to seek medical attention immediately.

Silo filler's disease, also known as silo-filler disease or silo filler lung, is a type of lung disease that occurs due to inhalation of nitrogen oxides from exposure to silage gas in recently filled silos. It can cause sudden death, pulmonary edema (fluid accumulation in the lungs), and bronchiolitis obliterans (a condition where the small airways in the lungs become narrowed). The exact synonyms for this disease are "Silo filler's disease" and "Silo filler lung".

Milk allergy is a type of food allergy, which occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly identifies proteins in cow's milk or other dairy products as harmful and attacks them. This can cause symptoms such as hives, itching, swelling, difficulty breathing, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis. Milk allergy is also known as lactose intolerance, although the two conditions are not the same. Lactose intolerance occurs when the body cannot digest lactose, a sugar found in milk and dairy products, due to a lack of lactase enzyme. In contrast, milk allergy involves an immune response to one or more proteins in cow's milk. It is important for individuals with milk allergy to avoid all dairy products and seek medical advice for safe alternatives.

Egg allergy is a type of food allergy that occurs when an individual's immune system reacts to proteins found in eggs. This can cause severe physical symptoms, such as itching or swelling of the mouth, throat tightness, and difficulty breathing. Egg allergy can be triggered by exposure to any egg product, including egg whites, yolks, and egg derivatives like lecithin. It is important for individuals with egg allergy to avoid foods that contain eggs or ingredients derived from eggs in order to prevent allergic reactions.

Peanut allergy is a type of food allergy that occurs when the immune system mistakenly identifies peanuts as harmful and responds by producing antibodies against them. This can lead to an allergic reaction, which may include symptoms such as itching or swelling of the face, throat tightness, difficulty breathing, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis. Peanut allergy is often caused by frequent exposure to small amounts of peanuts over time and can be managed through a strict avoidance of peanuts and other allergens, use of epinephrine auto-injector, and following an emergency action plan.

Nut allergy is a type of food allergy that occurs when the body's immune system reacts to nuts, causing various symptoms such as asthma, skin rashes, throat and eye irritation, and anaphylaxis. It develops from exposure to and particularly consumption of nuts. The exact synonyms for nut allergy are allergy to nuts and nut allergic reaction.

Autoimmune diseases of the nervous system are a class of disorders characterized by the immune system attacking healthy cells within the body. These diseases can affect various parts of the nervous system, including the brain, spinal cord, and nerves throughout the body. Some common examples include multiple sclerosis, Guillain-Barre syndrome, and chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (CIDP).

Autoimmune diseases of the nervous system can be challenging to diagnose due to the wide range of symptoms they may present. Symptoms can include pain, weakness, numbness or tingling in the limbs, balance and coordination problems, and difficulty with speech or swallowing.

Treatment options for autoimmune diseases of the nervous system depend on the specific condition but may involve medications to reduce inflammation, immunosuppressive therapies to suppress the immune response, plasma exchange (plasmapheresis) to remove abnormal antibodies from the blood, and physical therapy or rehabilitation to help manage symptoms and improve function.

It's important to note that autoimmune diseases of the nervous system can be unpredictable in their progression and may require long-term management to control symptoms and prevent further damage to the nervous system.

orbit alveolar rhabdomyosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects the muscles and connective tissues. It can occur in the orbit, which is the area around the eyes. This particular form of the disease has a distinct pattern of growth, characterized by poorly differentiated cells arranged in an alveolar pattern, separated by thin fibrovascular septa. It's important to note that there are different types and subtypes of rhabdomyosarcoma, and this specific one is classified as "alveolar."

Papillary squamous carcinoma is a type of squamous cell carcinoma that has papillae, which are characterized either by narrow fibrovascular cores that superficially resemble papillary carcinoma of the urinary tract or by broad cores that contain edematous fibrous stroma with prominent capillaries and stromal inflammation. It is also known as papillary epidermoid carcinoma.

Myofibroma is a type of connective tissue benign neoplasm that consists predominantly of mature and fully developed muscle fibers. It can occur in various parts of the body, including the arms, legs, neck, and trunk. The exact synonym for Myofibroma is Lipoleiomyoma.

Bone peripheral neuroepithelioma (also known as osseous peripheral Neuroepithelioma) is a rare type of cancer that affects the bones. It is a part of the Ewing sarcoma family, which are a group of rare, aggressive tumors that primarily occur in children and young adults. Ewing sarcoma is characterized by the presence of a specific genetic marker called EWS-FLI1, which is found in the cancer cells. Bone peripheral neuroepithelioma typically affects the extremities, particularly the legs, but can also occur in other bones. The symptoms include pain, swelling, and limited mobility. Treatment usually involves a combination of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery.

Soft tissue peripheral neuroepithelioma (also known as peripheral Neuroectodermal tumor of soft tissues) is a rare type of extraosseous Ewing sarcoma. It originates in the soft tissues surrounding the bones, particularly those in the legs and arms. These tumors are typically found in children and young adults, and they can be difficult to diagnose due to their rarity and non-specific symptoms. Treatment options for this type of cancer may include surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, depending on the specific characteristics of the tumor and the individual patient's condition.
Neuromuscular junction disease is a type of neuromuscular disease characterized by disfunction at the neuromuscular junction.

Reticulohistiocytic granuloma is a type of histiocytosis that has been described as having phenotypic characteristics similar to those of a granuloma. It is characterized by the presence of reticulin-rich macrophages, which are a type of histiocyte. Reticulohistiocytic granuloma can occur in various locations throughout the body and has been associated with a number of medical conditions, including cancer, autoimmune diseases, and infections. It is important to note that reticulohistiocytic granuloma is not a specific diagnosis, but rather a descriptive term used to describe a particular type of histiocytosis based on its characteristic appearance under the microscope.

text: spongiotic dermatitis is a type of dermatitis.

Phototoxic dermatitis is a type of irritant dermatitis that is caused or precipitated by exposure to ultraviolet (UV) sunlight, or by mediating phototoxic or photoallergic material in response to UV sunlight. It can cause skin redness and blistering, and is more common in areas of the body that are frequently exposed to sunlight. Treatment usually involves avoiding further sun exposure and using topical corticosteroids to reduce inflammation.

Folliculitis is a condition in which the hair follicles become inflamed or infected. It can cause small, red bumps to form around the affected hair follicles and may be itchy or painful. Folliculitis can occur on any part of the body but is commonly seen on the scalp, face, back, chest, pubic area, and legs.
It can be caused by a variety of factors such as bacterial infections (e.g., Staphylococcus aureus), fungal infections (e.g., pityrosporum ovale), viruses (e.g., human papillomavirus), and skin irritation from shaving or friction.
It can be treated with topical antibiotics, antifungal creams, or over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream to reduce inflammation. In some cases, oral antibiotics may be prescribed if the infection is severe or widespread. It is important to keep the affected area clean and dry and avoid scratching or picking at the bumps to prevent further irritation or infection.

Hepatitis E is a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the liver, has a material basis in the Hepatitis E virus, which is transmitted by ingestion of contaminated food. The infection causes symptoms such as fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, clay-colored bowel movements, dark urine, joint pain and jaundice.
Cervical melanoma is a type of cervical cancer that occurs when abnormal cells in the cervix are caused by an overproduction of melanin.

Fibrous histiocytoma is a type of histiocytoma that appears as an infiltrating growth pattern, characterized by the presence of large numbers of fibrous tissue and a lack of malignancy. It has been referred to with several different names, including Fibroxanthoma and benign fibrous histiocytoma, which are all synonymous terms for the same condition.

Cutaneous fibrous histiocytoma is a type of skin benign neoplasm, characterized by the formation of fibrous tissue in the skin. It can also be referred to as a fibrohistiocytic tumor, and it has been described as having similarities to both dermatofibroma and sclerosing angioma. Cutaneous fibrous histiocytoma can occur at any age but is more common in middle-aged individuals. It is a benign skin growth that does not have the potential to become malignant, although it may cause discomfort or cosmetic concerns for some patients due to its appearance or location.

:benign_deep_fibrous_histiocytoma rdfs:subClassOf :immune_system_organ_benign_neoplasm .
text: benign deep fibrous histiocytoma is a type of immune system organ benign neoplasm.

:malignant_adenofibroma rdfs:subClassOf :carcinosarcoma .
text: malignant adenofibroma is a type of carcinosarcoma.

Sea-blue histiocytosis, also known as sphingolipidosis, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to process and metabolize sphingolipids. This leads to the accumulation of abnormal sphingolipid molecules in various tissues of the body, including the liver, spleen, lungs, and brain.
Symptoms can include fever, weight loss, fatigue, hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), splenomegaly (enlarged spleen), cytopenia (low levels of blood cells), and neurological symptoms such as ataxia, dysarthria, and dementia.
Diagnosis is typically made through a combination of clinical examination, laboratory tests, imaging studies, and genetic testing. Treatment options for Sea-blue histiocytosis include enzyme replacement therapy, supportive care, and bone marrow transplantation in some cases.
It's important to consult a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan for this rare disorder.

Juvenile xanthogranuloma is a type of non-Langerhans cell histiocytosis, which is characterized by the presence of benign skin lumps or bumps caused by the accumulation of histiocytes. These lumps are initially red, orange or tan in color and may become more yellow over time. They typically appear on the head, neck, and trunk of the body. The exact synonyms for juvenile xanthogranuloma include multiple eruptive juvenile xanthogranuloma, naevoxanthoendothelioma, and xanthoma neviforme.

Dyslexia is a learning disability that affects an individual's ability to read and process written words. It is characterized by difficulties in phonemic awareness, decoding, and fluency. Dyslexia can also impact an individual's comprehension and spelling abilities. It is estimated that 10-20% of the population has dyslexia, and it can occur at any age. Early intervention and specialized instruction can help individuals with dyslexia to improve their reading skills and overcome the challenges associated with this learning disability.
Somatostatinoma is a type of neuroendocrine tumor. It can also be referred to as Somatostatin cell neoplasm or Somatostatin cell tumour.

Pancreatic somatostatinoma is a type of islet cell tumor, characterized by the production and secretion of somatostatin, a hormone that helps regulate various bodily functions. It is also known as pancreatic delta cell somatostatin-producing neoplasm. These tumors are usually benign and slow-growing, but in some cases, they can become malignant. Symptoms may include diabetes, weight loss, abdominal pain, and jaundice. Treatment options for pancreatic somatostatinoma depend on the size, location, and severity of the tumor, as well as the patient's overall health. In some cases, surgical removal of the tumor may be necessary. Radiation therapy and chemotherapy may also be used to treat more advanced or malignant tumors.

Pancreatic Delta cell neoplasm is a type of pancreatic cancer that affects the cells responsible for producing insulin, specifically in the pancreas. It's also referred to as Pancreatic Delta cell tumor or PDCT.

Small Intestine Neuroendocrine Tumor (SINET) is a type of small intestine benign neoplasm. It is characterized by the presence of hormone-producing cells, which are responsible for the production and release of various peptide hormones into the bloodstream. These tumors are typically slow-growing and non-invasive, meaning they do not spread to other parts of the body. However, if left untreated, SINETs can cause significant symptoms due to the excess hormone production, such as diarrhea, weight loss, abdominal pain, and malnutrition.

Treatment options for SINETs include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy. The choice of treatment depends on factors such as the size and location of the tumor, as well as the patient's overall health and medical history. In some cases, a combination of treatments may be necessary to achieve the best results.

It is important for individuals with SINETs to work closely with their healthcare team to develop an effective treatment plan and manage any associated symptoms. Regular follow-up appointments are also essential to monitor the progress of the disease and make any necessary adjustments to the treatment plan as needed.

Cavernous sinus meningioma, also known as cavernous sinus tumor or craniopharyngioma, is a type of brain tumor that originates in the cavernous sinus, which is a small channel located in the skull near the carotid canal and the optic nerve. It is a rare type of brain tumor, accounting for less than 5% of all primary brain tumors.

Cavernous sinus meningioma typically affects adults between the ages of 30 and 50, with women being more commonly affected than men. The symptoms of cavernous sinus meningioma can vary depending on the size and location of the tumor, but may include visual disturbances such as double vision or decreased vision in one eye, facial pain or numbness, swelling around the eye, and headaches.

The diagnosis of cavernous sinus meningioma typically involves a combination of imaging studies such as MRI or CT scans, as well as a biopsy to confirm the presence of cancer cells. Treatment options for cavernous sinus meningioma may include surgery, radiation therapy, and/or chemotherapy, depending on the size and location of the tumor and the patient's overall health.

It is important to note that while cavernous sinus meningioma can be a serious condition, it is also potentially curable with appropriate treatment. If you or someone you know has been diagnosed with this type of brain tumor, it is essential to seek advice from a qualified medical professional for proper evaluation and management.

Anterior cranial fossa meningioma is a type of tumor that affects the anterior cranial fossa, which is one of the four quadrants of the brain. It is also known as a meningioma of the Anterior Fossa. These tumors are typically non-cancerous and slow-growing, but they can still cause problems if they press on important parts of the brain or obstruct its blood vessels. Treatment for anterior cranial fossa meningiomas often involves surgery to remove as much of the tumor as possible while preserving normal brain function. Radiation therapy and/or chemotherapy may also be used in some cases, depending on the specific characteristics of the tumor and the patient's overall health.

That's correct! Skull base meningioma is a type of tumor that grows in the area around the brain and spinal cord. It is also known as meningioma of the skull base, and it can be benign or malignant.

Benign skull base meningiomas are usually slow-growing and do not spread to other parts of the body. However, they can still cause problems if they grow too large or press on nearby structures like nerves or blood vessels. Malignant skull base meningiomas, on the other hand, are more aggressive and can spread quickly to other parts of the body.

Treatment for skull base meningioma depends on factors such as the size and location of the tumor, as well as the patient's overall health. Options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or a combination of both. It is important to consult with a qualified medical professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Central nervous system germinoma is a type of central nervous system germ cell tumor that occurs when germ cells in the brain or spinal cord grow out of control. It is also known as CNS germinoma and germinoma of CNS.

Central nervous system germ cell tumor is a type of germ cell cancer that affects the brain and spinal cord. It develops from abnormal cells in the reproductive organs that have not matured before birth, and can spread to other parts of the body. Central nervous system germ cell tumors are rare, but can be serious if not treated early. They often require surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy to treat effectively.

Seminoma is a specific type of germ cell cancer that originates from cells with a material basis in sperm or egg cells. It is also known as pure germinoma, and it has the exact synonym Seminoma, Pure.
That's correct! Dysgerminoma is a type of ovarian cancer that arises from cells that give rise to egg cells. It is also known as germ cell cancer that originates in the ovary.

Cervical alveolar soft part sarcoma is a type of cancer that occurs in the cervix region of the uterus. It falls under the category of malignant neoplasm, and specifically, it's an alveolar soft part sarcoma that has grown in the cervical area.

:cystoid_macular_edema rdfs:subClassOf :macular_retinal_edema .
text: cystoid macular edema is a type of macular retinal edema.

Macular degeneration is a type of retinal degeneration that occurs when the light-sensitive cells in the macula, which is the central part of the retina responsible for sharp, detailed vision, begin to deteriorate. This can lead to gradual vision loss and difficulty seeing fine details. There are two main types of macular degeneration: dry (atrophic) and wet (neovascular or exudative). Dry macular degeneration is characterized by the slow breakdown of light-sensitive cells in the macula, while wet macular degeneration is caused by the growth of blood vessels under the retina. Both types can lead to vision loss if left untreated. Symptoms may include blurred or distorted vision, difficulty recognizing faces, and a blank spot in the center of the visual field. There is no cure for macular degeneration, but treatments such as laser therapy and anti-VEGF injections can help slow its progression and improve symptoms. It's important to consult an eye doctor regularly to monitor the condition and catch any changes early on.

Macular retinal edema, also known as macular oedema or macular retinal oedema, is a condition that affects the macula of the eye. The macula is the central part of the retina responsible for sharp, detailed vision. When the macula becomes swollen or inflamed, it can cause vision loss and other symptoms.

There are several causes of macular retinal edema, including diabetes, hypertension, and trauma to the eye. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms such as blurred vision, dark spots in your field of vision, or difficulty reading or recognizing faces. Treatment options may include medications, laser therapy, or surgery, depending on the underlying cause and severity of the condition.

It is worth noting that macular retinal edema can be a serious condition that may lead to permanent vision loss if left untreated. Therefore, it is crucial to consult an eye doctor if you suspect that you have this condition or if you experience any symptoms associated with it.

Bartter disease is a type of monogenic disorder that affects the renal tubules, specifically involving a deficiency in one of the four main enzymes responsible for reabsorbing sodium and potassium ions from the filtrate as it flows through the nephron. The deficiency results in an imbalance of electrolytes which can lead to symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and low potassium levels in the blood (hypokalemia). It is also characterized by increased urinary excretion of chloride and bicarbonate. The condition has a genetic basis and is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Renal cell carcinoma (RCC) is a type of renal carcinoma that originates in the lining of the proximal convoluted renal tubule of the kidney. It is also known as RCC, adenocarcinoma of the kidney, and hypernephroma.

Renal carcinoma is a type of kidney cancer that originates from the lining of the proximal convoluted tubule, which are the small tubes in the kidney responsible for filtering blood and removing waste products. It can also be referred to as carcinoma of the kidney or kidney carcinoma.
Childhood kidney cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma that develops during childhood or adolescence. It is also known as pediatric renal cell carcinoma.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:hereditary_renal_cell_carcinoma rdfs:subClassOf :renal_cell_carcinoma .
text: hereditary renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma.

Primary hyperaldosteronism (PH) is a condition in which the adrenal glands produce too much of the hormone aldosterone. This can lead to an increase in blood pressure and other health issues. The exact synonyms for PH are Cushing syndrome and hyperaldosteronism.

Multilocular clear cell renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of multiple cyst-like spaces within the tumor. These spaces are filled with clear, colorless fluid and are separated by thin walls. The term "cystadenocarcinoma" refers to the presence of both cysts and cancer cells in the same tumor, while "renal cystadenocarcinoma" specifically refers to this type of renal cell carcinoma.

Collecting duct carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma that begins in the distal collecting ducts of the kidney with a tubulopapillary morphology and intracytoplasmic mucicarminophilic material. It can also be referred to as carcinoma of renal Collecting duct, renal Medullary carcinoma, or renal carcinoma, collecting duct type.

papillary renal cell carcinoma is a type of kidney cancer characterized by the growth of multiple, bilateral papillary tumors. It can also be referred to as Chromophil carcinoma of the kidney or simply papillary kidney carcinoma. It is important to note that it is sporadic, meaning there is no known cause.

Clear cell renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of clear or pale cells when examined under a microscope. It has a defined material basis in these cells, making it distinct from other types of renal cell carcinoma. Other synonyms for clear cell renal cell carcinoma include Clear cell carcinoma of kidney, clear cell kidney carcinoma, conventional (Clear cell) renal cell carcinoma, and renal clear cell carcinoma. Additionally, clear cell renal cell carcinoma can be related to Clear-cell metastatic renal cell carcinoma.
Clear cell adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that originates from malignant mesonephric cells, which have clear cytoplasm.

renal tubular transport disease, also known as inborn renal tubular transport disorder, is indeed a type of kidney disease. The term "inborn" means that the condition is present at birth and is likely to be genetic in nature. It affects the normal functioning of the renal tubules, which are responsible for filtering waste products from the blood.

Symptoms of renal tubular transport disorder can include high levels of certain minerals in the blood (such as phosphorus and potassium), low levels of other minerals (such as calcium and magnesium), and abnormal electrolyte balance. These imbalances can lead to a range of symptoms, including nausea, vomiting, muscle weakness, and even life-threatening arrhythmias in severe cases.

Diagnosis typically involves blood tests and imaging studies (such as an ultrasound or CT scan) to evaluate kidney function and identify any abnormalities. Treatment may involve dietary changes, medication, and close monitoring of electrolyte levels. It is important for individuals with renal tubular transport disorder to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their condition effectively.

chromophobe renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma that is characterized by the presence of chromophobe cells, which are larger and have different features than clear cells. Other synonyms for this condition include Chromophobe carcinoma of kidney, chromophobe adenocarcinoma, kidney chromophobe, and renal cell carcinoma, chromophobe cell.

text: mucinous tubular and spindle renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma.

That is correct! Sarcomatoid renal cell carcinoma refers to a subtype of renal cell carcinoma that has spindle-shaped cells. This type of cancer is characterized by its distinctive appearance and can have a poorer prognosis than other types of renal cell carcinoma. It's important for patients to undergo appropriate treatment and follow-up care to manage their condition effectively.

:pseudohypoaldosteronism rdfs:subClassOf :renal_tubular_transport_disease .
text: pseudohypoaldosteronism is a type of renal tubular transport disease.

Achondroplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by short stature, rhizomelic shortening of the limbs, frontal bossing and midface hypoplasia, exaggerated lordosis, limitation of elbow extension, genu varum, and trident hand. It results in dwarfism due to abnormal ossification of cartilage in the long bone and is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor-3 gene (FGFR3) on chromosome 4p16.3. It has exact synonyms such as Achondroplastic physique, Chondrodystrophia, and osteosclerosis congenita.

allergic rhinitis is a type of respiratory allergy that occurs when the immune system overreacts to allergens in the environment. It causes inflammation and irritation of the nasal airways, leading to symptoms such as sneezing, runny nose, nasal congestion, itching, and tearing of the eyes. Allergic rhinitis can be caused by exposure to allergens such as pollen, dust mites, animal dander, mold, and cockroaches. It is also known as non-seasonal or perennial allergic rhinitis, atopic rhinitis, hay fever, pollenosis, and seasonal allergic rhinitis.

Rhinitis is a type of nasal cavity disease that involves irritation and inflammation of the mucous membrane in the nose. It can be caused by viruses, bacteria or irritants, leading to symptoms such as a runny nose, nasal congestion and post-nasal drip.

malignant biphasic mesothelioma is a type of malignant mesothelioma. Malignant biphasic mesothelioma has exact synonym Mesothelioma, biphasic, malignant. Additionally, it has exact synonym mixed Mesothelioma.

Sarcomatoid mesothelioma is a type of cancer that affects the lining of the lungs, chest wall, or other organs in the body. It is also known as malignant fibrous mesothelioma or spindled mesothelioma. The cancer cells are large and have a sarcoma-like appearance.
It is less common than other types of mesothelioma, but it tends to be more aggressive and has a lower survival rate. Symptoms may include chest pain, shortness of breath, cough, and fluid buildup in the chest. Diagnosis typically involves imaging tests such as CT scans or MRIs and a biopsy to remove a sample of cells for examination under a microscope. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and/or immunotherapy.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:malignant_epithelial_mesothelioma rdfs:subClassOf :malignant_mesothelioma .
text: malignant epithelial mesothelioma is a type of malignant mesothelioma.

Malignant peritoneal solitary fibrous tumor is a type of cancer that originates in the lining of the abdominal cavity, known as the peritoneum. It is characterized by the presence of prominent hemangiopericytoma-like vessels and is typically considered to be a subtype of pleural and peritoneal solitary fibrous tumor (SSFT).
It is important to note that there may be some variation in the terminology used to describe this type of cancer, with different sources using different terms such as malignant peritoneal solitary fibrous tumor, pleural and peritoneal SSFT, or malignant peritoneal SSFT. However, all of these terms generally refer to the same condition.

Persian Gulf Syndrome, also known as Gulf War Syndrome, is a term used to describe a group of symptoms that some veterans and civilian workers who were involved in the Persian Gulf War (1990-1991) have reported experiencing. These symptoms can include fatigue, muscle pain, headaches, joint pain, and other health problems. However, it's important to note that the exact cause of these symptoms is not yet fully understood, and there is ongoing research to determine what may be causing them.

avian influenza is a type of influenza that results in the infection located in the respiratory tract of humans, domestic and wild birds. It has five strains of avian influenza A viruses (H5N1, H7N3, H7N2, H7N7 and H9N2) known to cause human infections. It has symptoms such as fever, cough, sore throat, muscle aches, nausea, diarrhea, vomiting, neurologic changes, pneumonia, and acute respiratory distress. The avian influenza virus is transmitted by contact with infected poultry. It has an exact synonym of avian flu or bird flu.
Myotonic disease is a type of muscular dystrophy that is characterized by progressive muscle wasting and weakness.

Hypokalemia is a condition where the potassium levels in the blood are abnormally low. It can be caused by various factors such as excessive loss of potassium through sweating, diarrhea or vomiting, and certain medications. Symptoms of hypokalemia include muscle cramps, weakness, and irregular heartbeat. It is important to address this condition through proper medical treatment and a balanced diet that includes plenty of fruits and vegetables which are good sources of potassium.

Orofaciodigital syndrome, also known as oral-facial-digital syndrome, is a rare congenital disorder that affects the development of the face, mouth, and digits. It is characterized by a combination of malformations in these areas, which can include cleft lip and palate, absence of certain teeth, and abnormalities of the fingers and toes. The exact cause of orofaciodigital syndrome is unknown, but it may be related to genetic factors or exposure to certain environmental conditions during pregnancy. Treatment for orofaciodigital syndrome typically involves a combination of surgical and dental interventions, as well as speech therapy and other supportive care.

Central nervous system angiosarcoma is a rare type of cancer that affects the central nervous system (CNS). It originates in the inner lining of blood vessels and can be difficult to diagnose due to its similar symptoms with other CNS tumors. The treatment options for this condition are limited, but radiation therapy and chemotherapy may be used to manage the disease.

childhood angiosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects children and has the exact synonym pediatric angiosarcoma, paediatric hemangiosarcoma, and pediatric angiosarcoma. It is characterized by the presence of blood vessels in the tumor, which are responsible for the rapid growth and spread of the cancer cells. Treatment options for childhood angiosarcoma may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these treatments. The prognosis for this type of cancer can vary depending on factors such as the location and size of the tumor, as well as the overall health of the child. With proper treatment, there is hope for a cure or long-term remission.

Aorta angiosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects the aorta, which is a major blood vessel in the body. It is also known as aortic hemangiosarcoma. This disease can cause problems with blood flow and pressure in the aorta, which can lead to complications such as aneurysms or dissections. Aorta angiosarcoma is a rare condition, but it can be life-threatening if not treated promptly. Treatment typically involves surgery to remove the affected section of the aorta or replace the damaged section with a graft.

breast angiosarcoma is a rare type of breast cancer that originates from the blood vessels within the breast or underarm area. It is also known as hemangiosarcoma of the breast. The exact cause of breast angiosarcoma is not well understood, but it may be related to exposure to certain chemicals or radiation. Symptoms include a lump or swelling in the breast, nipple retraction, and skin irritation. Treatment typically involves surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:conventional_angiosarcoma rdfs:subClassOf :angiosarcoma .
text: conventional angiosarcoma is a type of angiosarcoma.

gallbladder angiosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects the gallbladder. It is characterized by the presence of malignant blood vessels, also known as angiosarcomas. These tumors can grow quickly and are often aggressive, which makes them difficult to treat. The exact cause of gallbladder angiosarcoma is unknown, but it is believed to be linked to chronic inflammation or infection in the gallbladder. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, bloating, and jaundice. If caught early, gallbladder angiosarcoma can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy. However, if it has spread to other parts of the body, treatment becomes more difficult and may involve a combination of these therapies. It is important for individuals who experience any of these symptoms to seek medical attention promptly.

User, you are correct. Thyroid angiosarcoma is indeed a type of thyroid sarcoma characterized by the presence of blood vessels in its cells. It results in a high prevalence of iodine-deficient goiter. To rephrase your statement with more precision: "Thyroid angiosarcoma is a specific subtype of thyroid sarcoma that exhibits the characteristics of both a sarcoma and an angiosarcoma, resulting in a high rate of iodine-deficient goiter."

Thyroid sarcoma is a rare type of cancer that originates in the thyroid gland, specifically in the supporting cells called C cell. It is also known as a sarcoma of the Thyroid gland. Symptoms may include a lump or swelling in the neck, hoarseness, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment options for thyroid sarcoma may involve surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and/or targeted therapy depending on factors such as tumor size, location, and stage of the cancer.

Skin Angiosarcoma is a rare type of skin cancer characterized by the rapid growth of abnormal blood vessels. It typically presents as an enlarged bruise or blue-black nodule on the skin, and may lead to ulcers that do not heal. The exact cause of Skin Angiosarcoma is unknown, but it can be linked to certain genetic changes and exposure to certain chemicals and radiation. Treatment options for Skin Angiosarcoma typically involve surgery to remove the affected area, along with follow-up treatments such as radiation therapy or chemotherapy to prevent recurrence.

Pleomorphic adenoma is a type of gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm. It is a benign neoplasm located in the salivary glands. The exact synonym for pleomorphic adenoma is "mixed tumor of the Salivary gland".

Cervical endometrial stromal sarcoma is a rare type of cancer that affects the cervix, which is the lower part of the uterus. It is also known as cervical stromal tumor or cervical stromal sarcoma. This condition occurs when the cells in the cervix grow abnormally and form a mass or tumor. These tumors are made up of cells that are similar to those found in the embryonic mesoderm, which is the tissue from which the muscles and connective tissues develop. While cervical endometrial stromal sarcoma can be aggressive, it is generally less common than other types of cervical cancer, such as squamous cell carcinoma or adenocarcinoma.

Cervix endometrial stromal tumor is a type of cervical cancer that originates from the fibrous connective tissue of the endometrium, which is the lining of the uterus. This type of cancer is also known as CES, and it can be located in the cervix or other parts of the reproductive system. It's important to note that while Cervix endometrial stromal tumor has a similar name to another type of cancer called endometriosis, they are not the same thing. Endometriosis is a condition where the tissue lining the uterus grows outside the uterus and can cause pain and other symptoms. Cervix endometrial stromal tumor, on the other hand, is a type of cancer that involves the fibrous connective tissue of the endometrium and can also cause pain and other symptoms but it's important to consult with a doctor for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Superior vena cava angiosarcoma is a type of angiosarcoma that originates in the walls of the superior vena cava, which is a large vein located in the upper part of the body. It can be difficult to diagnose and treat due to its location and rarity. Symptoms may include chest pain, swelling in the arms or legs, shortness of breath, and fatigue. Treatment options for superior vena cava angiosarcoma typically involve surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy. The prognosis for this type of cancer can be poor due to its aggressive nature and location within the body.

Prostate angiosarcoma is a rare and aggressive form of cancer that affects the prostate gland. It is characterized by the growth of abnormal blood vessels, which can cause the tumor to spread quickly throughout the body. Symptoms may include pain or discomfort in the lower back or rectal area, difficulty urinating, and blood in the urine or semen. Treatment options for prostate angiosarcoma typically involve a combination of surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy, with the aim of removing the tumor and preventing its further spread. However, due to the rapid nature of this disease, it can be difficult to fully remove all cancer cells, leading to a poor prognosis for patients.

Mediastinum angiosarcoma is a specific type of tumor that forms in the lining of blood vessels, which is called the endothelium. It is also known as hemangiosarcoma of the mediastinum when it occurs in this particular area. The term "mediastinum" refers to the tissue between the two lungs in the chest, and angiosarcoma is a type of cancer that arises from blood vessels. When these two terms are combined, we have the specific diagnosis of mediastinum angiosarcoma.

ovarian angiosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects the ovaries. It is characterized by the growth of malignant blood vessels in the ovary, which can lead to the spread of cancer to other parts of the body. Ovarian angiosarcoma typically has a poor prognosis and is often diagnosed at an advanced stage when it is difficult to treat effectively. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, but the overall survival rate for this type of cancer is quite low. It is important for patients to seek medical attention if they experience any symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, or difficulty eating, as these can be signs of ovarian cancer.

MEC stands for Mucoepidermoid Carcinoma, which is a type of carcinoma characterized by the presence of cuboidal mucous cells, goblet-like mucous cells, squamoid cells, cystic changes, and a fibrotic stromal formation. It has the exact synonym MEC.

Hallermann-Streiff Syndrome, also known as Francois dyscephalic syndrome and Hallerman-Streiff syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects growth and development. It is characterized by short stature, craniosynostosis (premature fusion of skull bones), and various dental abnormalities. The syndrome can also cause other health problems such as hearing loss, vision issues, and certain facial features like a low-set jaw, wide mouth, and a prominent forehead. Treatment typically focuses on managing the symptoms and improving quality of life.

Hypotrichosis is a medical condition characterized by sparse hair on the scalp. This can result from abnormal hair follicle development and mutations in proteins involved in hair growth, division or proliferation of cells within hair follicles. It's important to consult with a qualified healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.
dysgraphia is a writing disorder that affects the ability to write properly. It can cause problems with handwriting, spelling and organizing thoughts on paper.

Nominal Aphasia, also known as Anomic Aphasia, is a type of aphasia characterized by difficulty in retrieving the names and oral forms of words. It often accompanies other types of aphasia, such as Broca's Aphasia, which affects word-finding in sentences, and Wernicke's Aphasia, which is characterized by difficulty with understanding and using language.

Nominal Aphasia can make it challenging for individuals to communicate effectively, leading to frustration and isolation. Treatment typically involves working with a speech therapist who can provide exercises to improve word-finding skills and help the individual learn alternative words or phrases to replace those they struggle with. Additionally, support from family and friends and participation in support groups can be beneficial for individuals living with Nominal Aphasia.

Pituitary gland Basophilic adenoma is a type of pituitary adenoma, which is a benign tumor that originates from the cells of the pituitary gland. It is characterized by the presence of large amounts of basophils, a type of white blood cell, in the affected tissue. Basophilic adenomas are typically small and slow-growing, but can cause various symptoms if they press on nearby structures in the brain or produce excess hormones. Treatment options include surgical removal, medications to reduce hormone production, and radiation therapy.

Retrograde amnesia is a type of amnestic disorder where a person loses their pre-existing memories to conscious recollection. It can be caused by traumatic events, such as accidents or assaults, or by medical conditions like temporal lobe epilepsy or encephalitis. It is important for people who experience retrograde amnesia to seek medical attention and receive proper treatment in order to recover their lost memories.

Adult mesenchymal chondrosarcoma is a type of cancer that typically affects the cartilage and bone, usually in the leg or arm. It is a rare form of sarcoma, which is a type of cancer that originates from connective tissue cells. The tumor primarily consists of mature cartilage, with some areas of bone and other soft tissues present as well. Treatment options for adult mesenchymal chondrosarcoma depend on the stage and location of the tumor, but may include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

extraskeletal myxoid chondrosarcoma is a type of cancer that affects the cartilage and bone tissue. It is characterized by the presence of cartilage-like cells in a myxoid stroma, which is a type of connective tissue. These tumors tend to grow slowly and can occur in various parts of the body, including the arms, legs, trunk, and head. The exact synonym for this type of chondrosarcoma is extraosseous chondrosarcoma, which refers specifically to a cancer that affects cartilage but not bone tissue.

I understand what you are saying. Large cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that is characterized by the presence of large, round or polygonal-shaped cells with abundant cytoplasm. It's also known as large cell lung cancer when it affects the lungs.

Thymus large cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates in the thymus gland, which is located in the chest. The thymus gland plays an important role in the development and maturation of T-cells, which are a type of white blood cell that helps fight off infections and other diseases. Large cell carcinoma of the Thymus is another name for this type of cancer, and it is also referred to as thymic carcinoma. It is important to note that this type of cancer can be aggressive and difficult to treat, and it is often diagnosed at a later stage when it has already spread to other parts of the body.

This type of cancer is also known as Non-small-cell type neuroendocrine carcinoma of Ovary.

Lung large cell carcinoma is a type of lung cancer that is characterized by the presence of large cells in the tumor. It is one of the four main types of lung cancer, along with small cell lung cancer, squamous cell lung cancer, and adenocarcinoma of the lung. Lung large cell carcinoma can occur in both smokers and non-smokers and tends to have a better prognosis than small cell lung cancer. It is often treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy.

Oral leukoedema, also known as leukedema of the mouth, is a condition characterized by a white or gray discoloration of the mucous membranes in the mouth. It is often associated with edema of the spinous or Malpighian layer.

Ludwig's angina, also known as cellulitis of the floor of the mouth, is a medical condition characterized by inflammation and infection of the soft tissues beneath the tongue. It is named after Ludwig Rehn, who first described the condition in 1921.

Ludwig's angina can occur when there is a build-up of bacteria in the mouth or throat, which can lead to an infection if the body's immune system cannot effectively fight off the bacteria. Symptoms may include swelling and pain beneath the tongue, difficulty speaking or swallowing, fever, and a feeling of warmth or wetness around the affected area.

Treatment typically involves antibiotics and may also require the removal of any dead tissue caused by the infection. In some cases, patients may need to be hospitalized for further treatment and observation. With proper medical care, Ludwig's angina can be effectively treated and the risk of complications minimized.

Ascariasis is a type of parasitic infection caused by the roundworm Ascaris lumbricoides. The symptoms of ascariasis include abdominal pain, coughing up blood, difficulty breathing, fever, nausea and vomiting, and wheezing. It is usually spread through contaminated food or water, and can be prevented by washing hands regularly and cooking food thoroughly. Treatment for ascariasis typically involves medication to kill the parasite, along with supportive care to address any complications that may arise from the infection.

Yes, you are correct. Non-specific chronic endometritis is a type of endometritis that persists for an extended period without any known cause. It can affect the reproductive performance and overall health of the affected individuals.

Granulomatous endometritis is a type of inflammation that occurs in the uterus, characterized by the formation of granulomas. It can be caused by various factors such as infections, autoimmune disorders, and certain medications. Symptoms may include abnormal bleeding, pelvic pain, and fever. Treatment typically involves a combination of medical therapy and surgery to remove the affected tissue.

Subacute bacterial endocarditis is a type of infective endocarditis, characterized by inflammation of the inner lining of the heart (endocardium) caused by a subacute bacterial infection. Symptoms can include fever, chest pain, and fatigue. It is also sometimes referred to as SBE or Subacute endocarditis, lenta.

Choroid plexus meningioma is a type of brain tumor that occurs in the choroid plexus, which is a part of the brain that produces cerebrospinal fluid. It is also known as meningioma of the Choroid Plexus. This type of tumor is typically benign and slow-growing, but it can still cause symptoms if it presses on nearby structures in the brain. Treatment for choroid plexus meningioma usually involves surgery to remove as much of the tumor as possible, followed by radiation therapy to kill any remaining cancer cells.

Muscle benign neoplasm refers to the growth of abnormal muscle tissue, often resulting in a non-cancerous tumor. This condition can cause discomfort and may need to be surgically removed for treatment. It is also known as myomatous neoplasm or a muscle neoplasm.

Retinal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the retina, which is the thin layer of tissue at the back of the eye. It is also referred to as ocular cancer and retinal disease. Correct. Familial retinoblastoma, also known as hereditary retinoblastoma, is a type of retinoblastoma that occurs due to an inherited genetic mutation. It typically affects young children and can be treated with various methods such as surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

Retinoblastoma is a type of malignant tumor that originates in the retina, the innermost layer of the eye. Bilateral retinoblastoma specifically refers to the development of this tumor in both eyes, typically affecting young children. It is considered an aggressive form of retinoblastoma and requires prompt medical attention for effective treatment and preservation of vision. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiotherapy, or a combination of these approaches. Early detection and diagnosis are crucial in improving outcomes for patients with bilateral retinoblastoma.

Unilateral retinoblastoma is a rare type of cancer that affects only one eye. It typically occurs in young children, and if not treated promptly, can lead to blindness or other serious complications. Unlike bilateral retinoblastoma, which affects both eyes, unilateral retinoblastoma requires different treatment strategies, as it is a single tumor that can be more easily managed with surgery or other localized therapies. Early detection and diagnosis are crucial in treating this type of cancer effectively and preserving vision.

Intraocular retinoblastoma is a type of retinoblastoma that occurs within the eye and has not spread to other parts of the body. It is a malignant tumor of the retina, which can cause significant damage if left untreated. Early detection and prompt treatment are crucial for successful outcomes in managing this condition.

Extraocular retinoblastoma is a type of retinoblastoma that has spread from the soft tissues surrounding the eye or to the optic nerve beyond the margin of resection to other parts of the body. It can be a life-threatening cancer, and early detection and treatment are crucial in reducing the risk of complications and improving outcomes for patients.

Benign mastocytoma is a type of benign neoplasm that arises from mast cells. Mast cells are a type of white blood cell that play an important role in the immune system, and when they accumulate abnormally or divide uncontrollably, it can lead to the formation of a benign tumor known as mastocytoma. While this condition is not cancerous, it can cause symptoms such as itching, swelling, and pain, especially if it becomes large enough to press on surrounding tissues. Treatment options may include surgery, corticosteroids, or other medications, depending on the size, location, and severity of the mastocytoma.

Extracutaneous mastocytoma refers to a type of mast cell neoplasm that is characterized by the presence of mast cells outside the skin, in the surrounding tissues and organs. It can occur anywhere in the body and may cause symptoms such as itching, pain, swelling, and bleeding. Treatment options for extracutaneous mastocytoma include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy. In some cases, a combination of these treatments may be used to achieve the best results.

Indolent systemic mastocytosis, also known as ISM, is a type of systemic mastocytosis where the mast cells are activated and accumulate in various organs and tissues throughout the body. It is characterized by the production of excessive amounts of histamine and other inflammatory mediators, which can cause symptoms such as itching, redness, and swelling. ISM is typically a slow-growing tumor and does not usually spread to other organs or tissues. However, if left untreated, it can lead to organ dysfunction and failure. Treatment options for ISM include medications that target mast cells and their activation, as well as surgical removal of affected tissue.

Multiple chemical sensitivity (MCS) is a condition in which a person experiences adverse reactions to low levels of exposure to various chemicals. It is also known as 20th century disease, chemical AIDS, environmental illness, idiopathic environmental illness, and total allergy syndrome.

Thalamic disease is a type of brain disease that can result from injury or damage to the thalamus, which is a part of the brain responsible for relaying sensory information and controlling sleep patterns. It is characterized by Dejerine-Roussy syndrome, which involves the progressive loss of motor function and sensation in the extremities, as well as other symptoms such as pain, weakness, and difficulty speaking or understanding language. Thalamic disease can have a significant impact on a person's quality of life and may require medical treatment and support to manage the symptoms effectively.
