:elephantiasis rdfs:subClassOf :lymphedema .
text: elephantiasis is a type of lymphedema.

Lymphedema is a condition that occurs when the lymphatic system is unable to properly drain excess fluid and waste, causing swelling in affected areas. It can be caused by surgery or injury to the lymph vessels, infections, or certain cancer treatments. Lymphoedema is a term used interchangeably with lymphedema.

Extraosseous Ewing sarcoma, also known as primitive neuroepithelial tumor (PNET), is a type of cancer that starts in the tissue surrounding bones. It typically occurs in children and young adults, but can also affect older individuals. The exact cause of extraosseous Ewing sarcoma is unknown, but it is believed to be caused by genetic mutations or chromosomal abnormalities. Symptoms of extraosseous Ewing sarcoma may include pain in the affected bone, swelling, and limited mobility. Treatment typically involves a combination of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery to remove the tumor.

Nonparalytic poliomyelitis, also known as non-paralytic aseptic meningitis, is a type of motor neuron disease that results from the destruction of motor neurons caused by infection with one of three types of the poliovirus: Human poliovirus 1, Human poliovirus 2, or Human poliovirus 3. The infection is transmitted through contact with contaminated food or water, or by direct contact with the saliva of an infected individual. Symptoms include fever, sore throat, headache, vomiting, fatigue, neck stiffness, and muscle spasms. It does not cause paralysis, unlike its more well-known counterpart, poliomyelitis.

Alcoholic pancreatitis is a type of inflammation or swelling in the pancreas that is caused by excessive alcohol consumption. It occurs when the normal digestive enzymes in the pancreas are activated due to high levels of alcohol in the blood, causing damage to the pancreatic tissue and leading to pain, nausea, and other symptoms. This condition can be life-threatening if not treated properly. It is important for individuals who suffer from alcoholic pancreatitis to seek medical attention and follow a proper treatment plan that may include medications, lifestyle changes, and avoiding alcohol altogether.
Pancreatitis is a type of pancreas disease that is characterized by inflammation of the pancreas.

Essential tremor is a movement disorder characterized by involuntary, rhythmic muscle contractions and relaxations that cause shaking movements in the hands, arms, legs, head, or trunk. It typically affects both sides of the body and worsens with purposeful movement, such as writing or eating. Essential tremor is often a lifelong condition, but it may not progress to more severe symptoms over time. There are different types of essential tremor, including:

* Postural tremor: occurs when the person holds a position and tries to move, such as sitting down from a standing position or reaching for something.
* Kinetic tremor: occurs during purposeful movement, such as writing or typing on a computer.
* Cadence tremor: involves a rhythmic, alternating contraction and relaxation of muscles, which can be seen in the legs when walking.

Essential tremor is often diagnosed based on symptoms and physical examination, but further testing such as an electroencephalogram (EEG) or imaging studies may be done to rule out other conditions with similar symptoms. There is no cure for essential tremor, but medications can help manage the symptoms. In some cases, deep brain stimulation surgery may be considered as a treatment option.

Optic nerve astrocytoma is a type of high-grade glioma, which is characterized by the presence of malignant cells in the brain tissue. Optic nerve glioma refers to a tumor that originates from the optic nerve, while optic nerve astrocytoma specifically refers to a tumor made up of astrocytes (a type of glial cell) found within the optic nerve. This condition can be located in cranial nerve II and has been described as having synonyms like Astrocytic tumor of optic nerve and optic tract astrocytoma.

Optic nerve glioma, also known as optic nerve neoplasm or glioma of the optic nerve, is a type of brain tumor that originates from the optic nerve. It is an uncommon type of primary brain tumor and can occur in both adults and children. The exact cause of optic nerve glioma is not fully understood, but it may be related to genetic factors or exposure to radiation.
Symptoms of optic nerve glioma can include visual disturbances such as blurred vision, double vision, or loss of vision; pain around the eye or behind the forehead; and headaches. These symptoms can be caused by the tumor pressing on the optic nerve or other structures in the brain.
Optic nerve glioma is typically treated with surgery to remove as much of the tumor as possible, followed by radiation therapy to kill any remaining cancer cells. Chemotherapy may also be used in some cases. The prognosis for optic nerve glioma depends on several factors, including the size and location of the tumor, the patient's age and overall health, and the effectiveness of treatment. With proper treatment, many people with optic nerve glioma can experience significant improvements in their symptoms and quality of life.

Atypical polypoid adenomyoma is a type of adenomyoma that has distinct characteristics. It can be described as an adenomyoma with a biphasic polypoid lesion, which contains both myofibroblastic stromal cells and endometrial intraepithelial neoplasm. This type of adenomyoma is considered to have atypical features compared to other types, such as typical or clear cell adenomyomas, which are characterized by a different composition or distribution of cells.

Adenomyoma of the uterine corpus is a type of benign tumor that forms within the muscular and glandular tissue of the uterus. It is also known as an adenomyoma or uterine corpus adenomyoma. This condition is typically characterized by the presence of smooth muscle and endometrial glands, and it is considered a benign neoplasm of the uterus.
cervical adenomyoma is a type of cervical benign neoplasm that originates from gland and muscle components.

Camurati Engelmann disease, also known as osteosclerosis, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by increased bone density in the long bones. It is caused by mutations in the TGFB1 gene, which results in abnormal bone growth and development. The exact synonyms for this condition include diaphyseal dysplasia, Engelman's disease, and progressive diaphyseal dysplasia.

The trichorhinophalangeal syndrome type ii is a genetic disorder that is caused by mutations in the EXT1 and TRPS1 genes. It is characterized by multiple exostosis (growths on the bone), short stature, and cone-shaped ends located in the epiphysis. The disease also has symptoms such as sparse scalp hair, thin upper lip, and a rounded nose. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is sufficient to cause the disorder. It is also known by other names, including Langer-Giedion syndrome, trichorhinophalangeal dysplasia type II, and trichorhinophalangeal syndrome type 2.

Thyroid gland disease is a condition that affects the thyroid gland, which is located in the neck. The thyroid gland produces hormones that regulate various bodily functions, such as heart rate and cholesterol levels. When the thyroid gland becomes diseased or dysfunctional, it can lead to an imbalance of these hormones and cause a range of symptoms, including weight changes, fatigue, tremors, and heat sensitivity.
Thyroid gland disease is classified as an endocrine system disease, which means it affects the production or regulation of hormones in the body. Some common types of thyroid gland diseases include hypothyroidism (an underactive thyroid), hyperthyroidism (an overactive thyroid), and thyroid nodules (abnormal growths in the thyroid gland).
In some cases, thyroid gland disease can be managed through medication or surgery. It is important to seek medical attention if you are experiencing symptoms of thyroid gland disease, as prompt treatment can help prevent complications and improve quality of life.

Eunuchism is indeed a form of hypogonadism. Here's the re-written version with added context: Eunuchism, a term referring to the absence of mature male germ cells and testicular hormones, is a specific type of hypogonadism, which is characterized by underactive or non-functioning reproductive glands.

Central nervous system hemangioma is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, which refers to the abnormal growth of cells in the brain or spinal cord that can cause various symptoms. It is also known as a hemangioma of CNS, and it is derived from endothelial cells. The specific synonym for this condition is "hemangioma of CNS."

Fibrolamellar carcinoma is a type of hepatocellular carcinoma, which is characterized by the presence of laminated fibrous layers interspersed between the tumor cells. These polygonal, deeply eosinophilic tumor cells arise in non-cirrhotic livers. Another name for this type of cancer is fibrolamellar hepatocellular carcinoma. It can also be referred to as oncocytic hepatocellular tumor.
Hepatocellular clear cell carcinoma is a type of liver cancer that affects the hepatic cells. It is also known as clear cell carcinoma of the liver or hepatocellular carcinoma, clear cell type.

central nervous system mesenchymal non meningothelial tumor is a type of cancer that affects the central nervous system. It originates from abnormal proliferating cells in the mesoderm and can develop from mesenchymal tumors within the CNS that develops from meninges. The exact synonyms for this type of tumor include non-meningothelial mesenchymal tumor, non-meningothelial mesenchymal tumour, and central nervous system mesenchymal non-meningothelial tumour.

That's correct! Sclerosing hepatic carcinoma is a type of hepatocellular carcinoma, and it has the exact synonym "Sclerosing Hepatocellular Carcinoma." Is there anything else I can help you with?

pineal parenchymal tumor of intermediate differentiation is a type of pineoblastoma.
pineal parenchymal tumor of intermediate differentiation has exact synonym pineal parenchymal tumour of intermediate differentiation.
Adult pineal parenchymal tumor is a type of cancer that affects the pineal gland, which is located in the middle of the brain. It is also known as adult Pineal Parenchymal neoplasm.

Pineal gland cancer, also known as pineocytic tumor or malignant Pineal Region tumor, is a type of endocrine gland cancer that originates in the pineal gland, which is located in the brain. It is characterized by the uncontrolled growth and spread of cells in the pineal gland, leading to the formation of a tumor. Pineal gland cancer can be challenging to diagnose due to its location deep within the brain and the fact that it does not produce any noticeable symptoms until it has reached an advanced stage. Treatment options for pineal gland cancer may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these approaches. It is important to consult with a medical professional if you are experiencing any concerning symptoms related to the pineal gland or brain function in general.
Myoblastoma is a benign neoplasm that originates from muscle cells. It is also known as a benign granular cell tumor.

Malignant granular cell esophageal tumor is a type of cancer that develops in the esophagus, which is the tube that carries food from the throat to the stomach. It is characterized by the presence of granular cells, which are abnormal cells found in the lining of the esophagus.
Granular cell tumor of esophagus and granular cell tumour of oesophagus are other names for this condition. Malignant granular cell esophageal tumor is also known as malignant granular cell esophageal tumour.

Esophageal cancer is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer that occurs when abnormal cells in the esophagus grow and divide uncontrollably. It can occur in any part of the esophagus, including the upper, middle, or lower thirds, as well as the proximal or distal ends. The exact synonyms listed for esophageal cancer include: Ca lower third oesophagus, Ca middle third oesophagus, esophagus cancer, malignant neoplasm of distal third of esophagus, malignant neoplasm of lower third of oesophagus, malignant neoplasm of middle third of oesophagus, malignant neoplasm of proximal third of esophagus, and malignant neoplasm of upper third esophagus. Additionally, it can be referred to as a malignant tumor of the distal third of the esophagus or the proximal third of the esophagus, or as a malignant tumor of the middle third of the esophagus. It is important to note that this disease has its location in the esophagus and it is considered as one of the many types of esophageal diseases.

Malignant granular cell myoblastoma is indeed a type of skin cancer. It is characterized by the presence of malignant cells that are derived from muscle tissue (myoblasts) and have a characteristic appearance, known as "granular" due to their distinctive cytoplasmic inclusions. These tumors can occur anywhere on the body but are most commonly found on the head, neck, and trunk.
It's worth noting that while malignant granular cell myoblastoma is a serious condition, it is relatively rare and fortunately tends to be slow-growing. Early detection and treatment can improve outcomes for patients.

A vulvar granular cell tumor is a type of vulvar benign neoplasm that has been defined as a vulvar benign neoplasm of neural origin characterized by round to polyhedral cells with indistinct margins and granular cytoplasm due to the accumulation of lysosomes. They occur in ribbons or clumps separated by hyalinised stroma and collaged fibers with uniform, small and dark staining nuclei.
Cardiac granular cell neoplasm is a type of cardiovascular organ benign neoplasm that has the exact synonym granular cell tumor of Heart.

Mediastinal granular cell myoblastoma, also known as granular cell tumor of the mediastinum, is a rare type of neoplasm that originates from the cells of the mediastinum. It is characterized by the presence of small, round or oval cells with abundant eosinophilic granules. These tumors are typically slow-growing and have a good prognosis when treated properly. However, they can cause compression of nearby structures, such as the trachea or esophagus, which may require surgical intervention.

Granular cell tumor of the sellar region is a type of cancer that develops in the neurohypophysis or infundibulum, which are parts of the posterior pituitary gland. It is characterized by granular, eosinophilic cells with abundant intracytoplasmic lysosomes. Another name for this type of tumor is neurohypophysis granular cell tumor.

posterior pituitary gland neoplasm is a type of pituitary gland benign neoplasm.
posterior pituitary gland neoplasm has definition A pituitary gland benign neoplasm that arises from the neurohypophysis..
posterior pituitary gland neoplasm has exact synonym Posterior Pituitary tumor.

:hobnail_hemangioma rdfs:subClassOf :hemangioma .
text: hobnail hemangioma is a type of hemangioma.

Ehrlich tumor carcinoma is a type of breast carcinoma that originates from the epithelial cells lining the milk ducts. It is also known as invasive breast cancer because it spreads to other parts of the body. The term "Ehrlich's tumor" can refer to either an inflammatory breast cancer or a tumor caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV). However, it is important to note that using the term "tumor" to describe any abnormal growth in the body may not be entirely accurate since the term "cancer" specifically refers to malignant cells.

melioidosis is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection with Burkholderia pseudomallei, which can be transmitted by contact with contaminated water or soil. The symptoms of melioidosis include fever, respiratory distress, chest pain, and stomach pain. It is also known as Nightcliff gardener's disease, Pseudoglanders, Whitmore's disease, acute and fulminating melioidosis, and subacute and chronic melioidosis.

Adult cerebellar neoplasm, also known as a cerebellum tumor, is a type of cancer that affects the part of the brain responsible for balance and coordination. It typically occurs in middle-aged or older adults, and may cause symptoms such as dizziness, nausea, and difficulty with balance and coordination. Treatment options depend on the specific type of tumor present, but may include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.

Papillary meningioma of the cerebellum is a type of brain tumor that originates from the cerebellum. It is a benign tumor, which means it does not spread to other parts of the body and is usually slow-growing.
Papillary meningioma of the cerebellum is also known as cerebellar papilloma, and its exact synonym is Papillary meningioma of Cerebellum.

Rhabdoid meningioma is a type of brain tumor that originates from the protective lining surrounding the brain and spinal cord. It is also known as rhabdoid meningothelial cell tumor, which is a more descriptive term. These tumors are characterized by their rhabdoid cells, which have a unique appearance under the microscope.
Rhabdoid meningioma can occur at any age but is most common in children and young adults. It tends to grow quickly and may be aggressive, spreading to other parts of the brain or spine. Symptoms may include headache, vomiting, seizures, and changes in mental state or personality. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of imaging tests, such as MRI or CT scans, and a biopsy to examine the tumor cells under a microscope. Treatment options depend on factors such as the size and location of the tumor but may include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.

Childhood Cerebellar Neoplasm is a type of cancer that occurs in the cerebellum, which is part of the brain. It typically affects children and adolescents, and can be caused by genetic or environmental factors. The symptoms of this condition may include balance problems, coordination difficulties, and changes in speech or language. Treatment options for Childhood Cerebellar Neoplasm depend on the specific type and location of the tumor, as well as the overall health and age of the patient. In some cases, surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these treatments may be recommended. It is important to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Phencyclidine (PCP) abuse is a type of substance abuse that involves the recurring use of PCP drugs despite negative consequences. It can have severe and long-lasting effects on an individual's mental and physical health, including delusions, hallucinations, impaired memory and coordination, and even permanent brain damage or death in extreme cases.
It is important to note that PCP is a dangerous drug and should not be used recreationally or without proper medical supervision. If you or someone you know is struggling with PCP abuse, it is important to seek help from a qualified healthcare professional or a substance abuse treatment center.

Basosquamous carcinoma is a rare and aggressive form of skin cancer that arises from the basal cells. It is characterized by a mixture of squamous cell features, such as rete ridges and verrucous structures, and basal cell features like rosettes and clefts. The exact synonyms for this type of cancer include Basisquamous cell carcinoma, Metatypical carcinoma, and basosquamous cell carcinoma. It is important to note that while it may be less common than other forms of skin cancer, early detection and treatment are crucial in achieving the best possible outcome for patients.

Yes, adjustment disorder is a mental health condition characterized by an excessive or inappropriate emotional response to a stressful life event. It typically develops within three months of the stressful event and can include symptoms such as anxiety, depression, irritability, and changes in appetite or sleep patterns. The symptoms are more severe than would be expected for the given situation and last longer than would be typical for a normal response to the stressor. It is also sometimes referred to as adjustment disorder or stress-related disorder.

High-grade ependymoma is a type of high-grade glioma.
High-grade ependymoma is a type of cancer that originates in the ventricles of the brain, specifically in the ependyma, which is the cell lining of the cerebral ventricles. Ependymal cells are a type of glial cell found in the ventricle lining of the central part of the brain.
Ependymoma can be further classified into two types: well-differentiated and poorly differentiated. Well-differentiated ependymoma has features that closely resemble normal ependyma, while poorly differentiated ependymoma lacks these distinguishing characteristics. Both types of ependymoma are aggressive and fast-growing tumors, often leading to death if not treated promptly.
Ependymoma can be found in both children and adults but is more common in childhood. It is also more common in males than females. Symptoms may include headache, nausea, vomiting, and seizures, among others. Treatment usually involves surgery, followed by chemotherapy and radiation therapy.

:myxopapillary_ependymoma rdfs:subClassOf :benign_ependymoma .
text: myxopapillary ependymoma is a type of benign ependymoma.

Mixed glioma is a type of high-grade glioma that refers to a tumor composed of both glial and neuronal cells. It can be further classified into subtypes based on the specific cell types present in the tumor. Some common subtypes include:

* Astrocytic tumors: These tumors are made up of astrocytes, which are star-shaped brain cells that support and protect neurons. Examples include glioblastoma multiforme and anaplastic astrocytoma.
* Oligodendroglial tumors: These tumors are made up of oligodendrocytes, which are cells that produce myelin, the fatty substance that insulates nerve cells in the brain. Examples include glioblastoma multiforme and anaplastic oligodendroglioma.
* Ependymal tumors: These tumors are made up of ependytes, which are cells lining the ventricles (fluid-filled cavities) in the brain. Examples include glioblastoma multiforme and anaplastic ependymoma.

It is important to note that mixed gliomas can be more aggressive and difficult to treat than other types of tumors, due to their complex composition and the potential for multiple subtypes to be present within a single tumor. Surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and targeted drug therapies may all be used in the treatment of mixed gliomas, depending on the specific subtype and stage of the tumor.

SEGA stands for Subependymal giant cell astrocytoma. It is a type of subependymal glioma, which is a rare and benign brain tumor that occurs in the cerebellum or brainstem region of children and young adults. SEGAs are usually not life-threatening but can cause symptoms such as headache, nausea, vomiting, balance problems, and weakness in one or both sides of the body. Treatment options for SEGA depend on its size and location, but may include surgery, radiation therapy, and/or chemotherapy.
Ganglioglioma is a type of benign neoplasm that arises from the glial cells in the central nervous system. It is also known as CNS ganglioglioma, adult ganglioglioma, or childhood ganglioglioma.

text: mixed epithelial stromal tumour is a type of mixed cell type cancer.

Sternum cancer is a type of bone cancer that occurs in the sternum, which is a part of the chest wall. It can cause symptoms such as chest pain and difficulty breathing due to compression of the lungs or airway obstruction by the tumor. Treatment options depend on the stage and location of the cancer, but may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and targeted therapies. It's important for individuals with sternum cancer to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Thoracic cancer refers to a group of cancers that originate in the thoracic cavity, which is the area between the neck and abdomen. This includes the lungs, esophagus, trachea, and chest wall. It is considered an organ system cancer, meaning it affects the respiratory system specifically. Some common types of thoracic cancer include lung cancer, esophageal cancer, and thymoma.

Middle ear cancer is a type of ear cancer that occurs in the middle ear, which is the part of the inner ear responsible for hearing. It can also be referred to as neoplasm of the middle ear or tumor of the middle ear.

Middle Ear Disease (MED) refers to a range of disorders that affect the middle ear, which is also known as the inner ear. The middle ear contains three small bones called ossicones, and this part of the ear helps in transmitting sound from the outer ear to the inner ear through the eustachian tube.

There are various types of MED, including Otitis Media (OM) or acute middle ear infection, which occurs when there is a buildup of fluid behind the eardrum. Other types of MED include Otitis Interna (OI), also known as labyrinthitis, and Cholesteatoma, which is an abnormal growth of skin in the middle ear.

Symptoms of MED may include fever, hearing loss, dizziness, and a feeling of fullness or pressure in the ears. In severe cases, MED can lead to complications such as facial weakness, vertigo, or even deafness if not treated promptly.

Treatment for MED depends on the severity of the condition and may include antibiotics, earwax removal, or surgery in some cases. It is essential to consult a healthcare professional if you experience any symptoms of MED to receive an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Ear cancer, also known as acoustic neurinoma or malignant otomastoid tumor, is a type of cancer that affects the auditory system. It occurs when healthy cells in the inner ear become abnormal and grow uncontrollably, leading to the formation of a tumor. The symptoms of ear cancer may include hearing loss, dizziness or vertigo, facial weakness, and balance problems. If left untreated, ear cancer can spread to other parts of the body and become life-threatening. Early detection and prompt treatment are crucial in ensuring a successful outcome for those diagnosed with this type of cancer.

Inner ear cancer, also known as acoustic neurinoma, is a type of cancer that affects the inner ear. It occurs when healthy cells in the inner ear grow uncontrollably and form tumors. These tumors can be benign or malignant and may cause symptoms such as hearing loss, balance problems, ringing in the ears (tinnitus), facial weakness, and even paralysis.
Ear cancer is a term used to describe cancer that occurs in any part of the ear, including the outer, middle, and inner ear. Inner ear cancer specifically refers to cancer that develops in the inner ear region and affects the cranial nerve responsible for hearing and balance. It's essential to note that not all cancers in the ear are located in the inner ear; some can also occur in other parts of the ear such as the outer or middle ear.
It is important to consult a healthcare professional if you experience any symptoms associated with inner ear cancer, such as hearing loss, balance problems, ringing in the ears, facial weakness, or paralysis. Early diagnosis and treatment can greatly improve outcomes for patients with this condition.

Testicular infarct is a type of testicular disease that occurs when the blood flow to the testicles is blocked, causing tissue death. The exact synonyms for testicular infarct are "infarction of the testis" and "testicular infarction."

Copper Deficiency Myelopathy is a condition that occurs due to a deficiency of copper, resulting in symptoms such as spastic gait and ataxia, often accompanied by anemia and neutropenia. It has been described as a type of nutritional deficiency disease or human swayback.

Nutritional deficiency diseases are a group of illnesses caused by a lack of essential nutrients in the diet. These diseases can lead to various health problems if left untreated. Some common examples include Vitamin A deficiency, which can result in night blindness, and Iron-deficiency anemia, which causes fatigue and weakness. To prevent these types of diseases, it is important to maintain a balanced diet that includes a variety of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats.

Dermoid cyst of ovary is a type of ovarian benign neoplasm.
Dermoid cyst of ovary is a type of dermoid cyst.
Dermoid cyst of ovary is a type of growth that occurs in the ovary.
Dermoid cyst of ovary has definition A growth in the ovary that is similar to a cyst but contains hair follicles, sweat glands, and sometimes other tissues.

Ovarian cystic teratoma is a type of ovarian tumor that is composed of both cystic and teratomatous tissue. It is also known as a mature teratoma, which means it contains all three germ cell layers: the outer layer (epidermis), the middle layer (dermis), and the inner layer (mesoderm). These tumors are typically benign but can become malignant in rare cases. Symptoms may include abdominal pain or bloating, irregular menstrual cycles, or pelvic mass, and they are usually diagnosed through imaging techniques such as ultrasound or CT scan. Treatment options depend on the size and location of the tumor, but surgical removal is often recommended.

epididymal neoplasm is a type of testicular cancer that occurs in the epididymis, which is a small gland located at the back of the testicle. It is also known as neoplasm of the epididymis.

Thoracic benign neoplasm is a type of abnormal growth that occurs in the chest area. It can be made up of different types of cells, such as muscle, connective tissue or blood vessels. Leiomyoma is another name for this type of tumor and it comes from smooth muscle cells. Mediastinum leiomyoma specifically refers to a type of leiomyoma that occurs in the mediastinum, which is the area between the lungs in the chest.

Fallopian tube leiomyoma is a type of benign neoplasm that forms in the fallopian tubes. It is also known as a fibroid tumor or uterine fibroid, and is made up of smooth muscle cells. These growths are typically non-cancerous, but can cause problems if they become too large or press against other organs or structures within the body.
Extrahepatic bile duct leiomyoma is a type of benign neoplasm that derives from smooth muscle cells and is located in the extrahepatic bile duct.

Central nervous system leiomyoma is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, which can be defined as a tumor derived from smooth muscle cells that occurs within the central nervous system. It is also known as leiomyoma of the CNS.

Bizarre leiomyoma is a type of uterine fibroid that has distinctive characteristics. It typically appears normal in appearance, but may have large, abnormal-looking nuclei and rare or absent mitotic figures. Other synonyms for this condition include atypical leiomyoma, pleomorphic leiomyoma, and symplastic leiomyoma.
Deep leiomyoma is a type of leiomyoma characterized by its location in the deep soft tissue, as opposed to the superficial or surface-level tissue.

Leiomyoma cutis, also known as cutaneous leiomyoma or skin leiomyoma, is a benign tumor that arises from the dermis of the skin. It is characterized by its smooth, fibrous texture and can appear red, tan or brown in color. Leiomyoma cutis usually measures less than 5 centimeters (2 inches) in diameter, but it can be larger in some cases.
It is important to note that while leiomyoma cutis is not cancerous, it can still cause discomfort or appearance-related issues if it grows too large or becomes irritated. If you have concerns about a skin growth, it's always a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and treatment recommendations.

Lung leiomyoma is a type of benign tumor that originates in the smooth muscle cells of the lung. It is also known as pulmonary leiomyoma.

Pericardium leiomyoma is a type of pericardial disease characterized by the presence of a benign tumor, also known as a leiomyoma, in the pericardium. The exact synonym for this condition is leiomyoma of the pericardium.
Leiomyomatosis is a type of leiomyoma that is characterized by the presence of multiple, diffuse smooth muscle fibers. It is also sometimes referred to as "uterine fibroids" or simply "fibroids."

Cellular leiomyoma is a type of uterine fibroid that has a higher concentration of cellular material than usual. It is characterized by its smooth, rounded appearance and lacks any atypical or abnormal cells. This type of fibroid is more common in women of childbearing age and can cause discomfort, heavy menstrual bleeding, and other symptoms. However, it does not typically require surgical intervention unless it becomes large enough to cause significant problems or displaces surrounding organs.

Gallbladder leiomyoma is a type of gallbladder benign neoplasm, which means it is a non-cancerous growth in the gallbladder. It is also referred to as leiomyoma of the gallbladder. These tumors are made up of smooth muscle cells and can cause problems if they grow too large or press on nearby organs. In some cases, gallbladder leiomyomas may require surgical removal.
Vulvar leiomyoma is a type of non-cancerous tumor that develops in the smooth muscle cells of the vulva.

Leiomyoma, also known as a fibroid tumor, is a benign growth made up of smooth muscle cells. They can occur in various parts of the body, including the uterus, ovaries, and large intestine (also called the colon). In the context of the large intestine, it is referred to as a leiomyoma of the colon or a leiomyoma of the large bowel. These tumors are typically non-cancerous, but they can cause problems if they become too large and press on surrounding organs or obstruct the normal flow of waste through the intestine. Surgical removal is often required to treat them.

Appendiceal leiomyoma is a benign neoplasm that arises from smooth muscle cells and is located in the vermiform appendix. It can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, and changes in bowel movements due to its location within the gastrointestinal tract. Treatment options include surgical removal of the affected portion of the appendix, with the goal of preserving as much of the normal structure as possible.

Dartoic leiomyoma has the definition of a reproductive organ benign neoplasm that has its material basis in the dartos muscle, which is located in the scrotum or labia majora.

Borna disease is a type of viral infectious disease that affects the central nervous system. It has a material basis in the Borna disease virus and is transmitted by contact with infected oronasal secretions. The infection can result in symptoms such as mood disturbances, behavioral disturbances, cognitive disturbances, neurologic disturbances, and movement impairment. It is also known as Enzootic encephalomyelitis and has a MESH code of D001890.

Uterine corpus sarcoma is a type of uterine cancer that originates in the muscles or supportive tissues of the uterus. It can also be referred to as sarcoma of the uterus. This condition is relatively rare and may not respond well to traditional chemotherapy or radiation therapy, making it essential for doctors to consider alternative treatment options such as immunotherapy or targeted therapy. It's important for patients to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop a personalized treatment plan that addresses the unique needs and challenges of each individual case.

ovarian endometrioid stromal sarcoma is a type of ovarian cancer that arises from the endometrial stromal tissue. It has a defined clinical and pathologic features, which helps in its diagnosis and treatment. The symptoms of this cancer may include abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and pelvic mass. A proper diagnosis is essential for an accurate prognosis, and it can be done through various diagnostic tests such as ultrasound, CT scan, MRI, and biopsy. Treatment options depend on the stage of cancer but may include surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy. It's important to consult a medical professional for proper evaluation and management.
